'this' Keyword (Self Reference) ğŸ§
ğŸ§  Logic:$\ mathbf {`this`}$ keyword ek reference variable hai jo hamesha us object ki taraf ishara karta hai jisne method ko call kiya hai (yaani, current object).Iska mukhya upyog Class ke andar $\mathbf{Instance~Variables}$ (object variables) aur $\mathbf{Local~Variables}$ (method ya constructor ke andar ke variables) ke beech ke naam ke conflict (takraav) ko hatane ke liye hota hai.ğŸ“Œ Example:Javaclass Student {
    String name;  // Instance Variable

    // Constructor mein 'name' local variable bhi hai
    Student(String name) { 
        // local variable 'name' instance variable 'name' ko shadow kar raha hai
        // isliye hum instance variable ko refer karne ke liye 'this.name' use karte hain
        this.name = name; 
    }

    void printName() {
        System.out.println(this.name); // Current object ka name print karega
    }
}
ğŸ”¤ Java Code:Javaclass Box {
    int height;
    
    // 1. Constructor mein this ka upyog
    Box(int height) {
        this.height = height; 
    }
    
    // 2. Doosre constructor ko call karne ke liye this ka upyog (Constructor Chaining)
    Box(int h, int w) {
        this(h); // Calls the single-parameter constructor
        // width = w;
    }
    
    // 3. Current object ko method ke argument mein pass karna
    void compare(Box otherBox) {
        if (this.height > otherBox.height) {
            System.out.println("Current box is taller.");
        }
    }
}

public class ThisKeywordDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Box b1 = new Box(20);
        Box b2 = new Box(10);
        
        b1.compare(b2); // Output: Current box is taller. (b1 'this' hai)
    }
}
ğŸ§¾ Notebook Points:JavağŸ“˜ 'this' Keyword:
â†’ Reference to the Current Object
â†’ Used to resolve conflict b/w Instance and Local variables (e.g., this.name = name)
â†’ Used to call one constructor from another (e.g., this(parameters))
